# Runbook — common operations

For why this is set up the way it is, see [ARCHITECTURE.md](./ARCHITECTURE.md).

---

## First-time setup (per repo, once)

Before the first deploy will work, configure these in GitHub:

**Branch protection + environment rules** (one command):

```bash
export GITHUB_TOKEN=<pat with repo + admin:org>
python scripts/setup_branch_protection.py \
    --repo {{.github_org_repo}} \
    --team {{.github_codeowners_team}}
```

This applies:
- `main` requires PR + CODEOWNERS review + passing validators.
- `prod` environment requires platform-team approval + 5-min cooling window.
- Both environments are restricted to deploys from `main`.

**Workspace-side lockdown** (one-time per workspace, done by the workspace
admin): see [`PROD_LOCKDOWN.md`](./PROD_LOCKDOWN.md). Without this, manual
deploys from a laptop or the workspace UI still succeed.



**Environments** (Settings → Environments): create `dev` and `prod`.

**Per-environment variables** (Settings → Environments → \<env\> → Variables):

| Variable | Value |
|---|---|
| `DATABRICKS_HOST` | workspace URL for that env |
| `DATABRICKS_CLIENT_ID` | CI service principal client_id |
| `UC_CATALOG` | catalog name for that env |
| `UC_WAREHOUSE_ID` | SQL warehouse the CI SP can use for `GRANT` |

**Per-environment secrets**:

| Secret | Value |
|---|---|
| `DATABRICKS_CLIENT_SECRET` | CI SP secret |

**One-time platform admin work** (ask the Lakebase admin):

- Make the CI SP an owner of the Lakebase instance, OR
- Grant the CI SP `CREATEROLE`, `CREATEDB`, and `WITH GRANT OPTION` on the
  schemas listed in `permissions.yaml`.

Without this, `apply_grants.py` will fail with permission-denied.

